{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No TN needed — \"category theory\" is unambiguous in English",
    "content": "No TN needed. Do not add one.\n\n\"Category theory\" is an established term in English with a clear referent: the branch of mathematics developed by Eilenberg and Mac Lane. Any reader literate enough to be reading this collection will either (a) already know what category theory is and not confuse it with Kant, or (b) not know what it is and look it up, at which point they will find the mathematical sense immediately.\n\nThe Kantian overlap is real but it is the author's job to manage, not the translator's. And the author does manage it -- the essays introduce objects, morphisms, functors, and universal properties with mathematical definitions. No reader who encounters \"let E be a category with objects and morphisms\" will think of the Critique of Pure Reason.\n\nA TN saying \"not to be confused with Kant's categories\" would be patronizing to readers who know the difference and confusing to readers who do not know either term. It would also plant a false worry: the reader who was not thinking about Kant would now start wondering whether they *should* be, creating a distraction the author did not intend.\n\nThe one place where a brief note *might* be warranted is in the dictionary/glossary (not in the text), noting that the Chinese term 范畴 carries both the Kantian and mathematical senses, and that the author is aware of this resonance. But this belongs in the translator's introduction or glossary, not as an inline TN."
  }
}
